
CREATION:
CREATE TABLE <table_name> (
	<column1_name> <datatype> [additional parameteres] PRIMARY KEY,
	<column2_name> <datatype> [additional parameteres],
	...
	<columnN_name> <datatype> [additional parameteres]
);

TEXT -> string
INT -> numeric
DECIMAL -> has decimal point
NOT NULL -> to insert a row, you need to fill in this space

example:
CREATE TABLE users (
	user_id INT PRIMARY KEY,		(psql: user_id int GENERATED ALWAYS AS IDENTITY PRIMARY KEY)
  	name TEXT NOT NULL,				(psql: name varchar(50) NOT NULL UNIQUE)
  	pass TEXT NOT NULL,				(psql: pass varchar(50) NOT NULL UNIQUE)
  	age DECIMAL(2, 0) NOT NULL
);

(any string/text is with single quotes)
DECIMAL(2, 0) means it can be 2 digits, and 0 digits to the right of the decimal point




ALTER:

ALTER TABLE <table_name>
ADD <columnN_name> <datatype> [additional parameters];

ADD -> adds a new column, updating the table structure

example:
ALTER TABLE users
ADD email TEXT NOT NULL;

altering a cloumn: (example, altering age to be a string) (sqlite doesnt allow)
ALTER TABLE users
ALTER COLUMN age TEXT;




DROP:
DROP TABLE <table_name>;
(BE VERY CAREFUL!!!!!!!, "DROP <table_name>;" DELETES THE TABLE AND ALL ITS DATA!!!!!!!!!!!)

example:
DROP TABLE users;




INSERT:
INSERT INTO <table_name> (<column2>, <column1>, ...)
VALUES (<value2>, <value1>, ...), (<value2>, <value1>, ...);
(as long as the column corresponds to the value, everything is good)
(can insert multiple rows in the same sql command)

example:
INSERT INTO users (user_id, name, pass, age)
VALUES (
	1,
	'Bruno',
	'safe_pass_lol',
	22
);



DELETE:
DELETE FROM <table_name>
WHERE <condition>;
(BE VERY CAREFUL!!!!!!!, "DELETE FROM <table_name>;" without filtering condition deletes all rows!!!!!!!!!!!)

example
DELETE FROM users
WHERE age < 24;




UPDATE ... SET ...:

UPDATE <table_name>
SET <column1> = <new_value1>,
	<column2> = <new_value2>,
	...
WHERE <condition>;
(BE VERY CAREFUL!!!!!!!, "UPDATE ... SET ...;" without filtering condition updates all rows!!!!!!!!!!!)


example:
UPDATE users
SET pass = 'yet_another_safe_pass',
	name = 'another_name'
WHERE age > 24;





RELATED TABLES and how to manage:

example:
product:						review:
product_id INT PRIMARY KEY \	review_id INT PRIMARY KEY
name TEXT 					\	review_text
price DECIMAL(5, 2)			 \	date DATETIME
manufacturer TEXT			  \	product_id INT
product_id in product is primary key.
product_id in review is a foreign key.

a parent table (product) uses a shared column between tables as its primary key
a child table (review) holds a foreign key

(parent table syntax is the same)
child table -> you need to specify a foreign key that references a primary key in the parent table
CREATE TABLE <child_table_name> (
	<child_table_id>  PRIMARY KEY,
	<parent_table_id>,
	... ,

	CONSTRAINT fk_parent_child
		FOREIGN KEY (parent_table_id) REFERENCES
		parent_table_name(parent_table_id)
);

example:
(this example is badly made, user_id is the owner)
